Argus - Passive Network Sniffer
===============================================================================

CSE 363: Offensive Security - Homework 1
Stony Brook University, Spring 2026


DESCRIPTION
-----------

Argus is a passive network sniffer that monitors HTTP, TLS, and DNS traffic.
It uses Scapy to capture and parse packets, supporting both live capture and
offline pcap analysis. Argus detects protocols regardless of the port number
used, making it useful for identifying hidden services on non-standard ports.

Supported protocols:
  - HTTP GET/POST/PUT requests (with automation/script detection)
  - TLS ClientHello messages (with SNI extraction)
  - DNS A record queries (with internal infrastructure TLD detection)


DEPENDENCIES
------------

  - Python 3 (tested with Python 3.11+)
  - Scapy (pip install scapy, or apt install python3-scapy on Kali Linux)
  - cryptography (apt install python3-cryptography, usually pre-installed)

All dependencies are pre-installed on Kali Linux 2025.4.


USAGE
-----

  ./argus.py [-i interface] [-r tracefile] [expression]

  -i interface    Live capture from the specified network interface (e.g., eth0).
                  If not specified, Scapy auto-selects a default interface.

  -r tracefile    Read packets from a pcap file (tcpdump format). Overrides -i.

  expression      Optional BPF filter (same syntax as tcpdump). Examples:
                    host 192.168.0.123
                    port 80 or port 443
                    src host 10.0.0.1 and tcp

Examples:

  # Live capture on eth0:
  sudo ./argus.py -i eth0

  # Read from a pcap file:
  ./argus.py -r capture.pcap

  # Live capture with BPF filter:
  sudo ./argus.py -i eth0 host 192.168.1.100

  # Analyze test trace:
  ./argus.py -r test.pcap


TECHNICAL APPROACH
------------------

Port-Independent Protocol Detection:

  Standard tools rely on well-known port numbers (80, 443, 53) to identify
  protocols. Argus instead inspects packet payloads to detect protocols on
  any port:

  DNS:  Checks if UDP payload parses as a valid DNS query with A record type.
        Scapy's DNS layer handles standard port 53 automatically; for
        non-standard ports, the raw UDP payload is manually parsed as DNS.

  HTTP: Checks if TCP payload begins with "GET ", "POST ", or "PUT ".
        Scapy's HTTP layer handles port 80 automatically; for non-standard
        ports, the raw TCP payload is parsed for HTTP request lines and
        headers (Host, User-Agent).

  TLS:  Checks TCP payload for the TLS handshake signature:
          byte[0] = 0x16 (handshake content type)
          byte[1] = 0x03 (TLS major version)
          byte[5] = 0x01 (ClientHello handshake type)
        SNI is extracted from the Server Name Indication extension. If Scapy's
        TLS parser fails, a manual binary parser extracts SNI from raw bytes.

Automation Detection:

  HTTP User-Agent strings are checked against known automation patterns:
  curl, wget, python-requests, python-urllib, python-httpx, libwww-perl,
  go-http-client, httpie. Matching requests are flagged with "AUTOMATION".

Internal Infrastructure Detection:

  DNS queries for domains ending in .local, .corp, or .internal are flagged
  with "INTERNAL" as these TLDs are indicative of internal infrastructure.


OUTPUT FORMAT
-------------

  TIMESTAMP PROTO SRC_IP:SRC_PORT -> DST_IP:DST_PORT [protocol-specific fields]

  DNS:  timestamp DNS  src:port -> dst:port domain [INTERNAL]
  HTTP: timestamp HTTP src:port -> dst:port host METHOD path [AUTOMATION ua]
  TLS:  timestamp TLS  src:port -> dst:port hostname|NO SNI


TEST TRACE (test.pcap)
----------------------

The test trace contains 12 packets covering all required cases:

  #  Protocol  Port        Case
  1  DNS       53 (std)    Normal domain (www.cs.stonybrook.edu)
  2  DNS       5353        Normal domain on non-standard port
  3  DNS       53 (std)    Internal domain (.local)
  4  DNS       1053        Internal domain (.corp) on non-standard port
  5  HTTP GET  80 (std)    Normal browser User-Agent
  6  HTTP GET  8080        Normal browser User-Agent on non-standard port
  7  HTTP POST 80 (std)    Automation detected (curl)
  8  HTTP PUT  9090        Automation detected (python-requests) on non-standard port
  9  TLS       443 (std)   ClientHello with SNI (google.com)
  10 TLS       993         ClientHello with SNI on non-standard port
  11 TLS       443 (std)   ClientHello without SNI
  12 TLS       8443        ClientHello without SNI on non-standard port


FILES
-----

  argus.py              Main sniffer tool
  README                This file
  test.pcap             Test traffic trace with all 12 cases
  test.out              Output of ./argus.py -r test.pcap
  generate_test_pcap.py Helper script to regenerate test.pcap
